This report presents the results of the transportation impact analysis (TIA) conducted for the proposed
Rocketship School in San Jose, California. The site is located at 3167 Senter Road, just south of
Capitol Expressway. The project site is currently occupied by a church. The proposed project would
replace the existing use with a K-5 charter elementary school with an enrollment of 600 students and
32 full-time staff. The project proposes a single entrance driveway and a single exit driveway on Senter
The potential impacts related to the proposed development were evaluated following the standards and
methodologies set forth by the City of San Jose and the Santa Clara Valley Transportation Authority
(VTA). The VTA administers the County Congestion Management Program (CMP). The traffic study
includes an analysis of AM and PM peak hour traffic conditions for fourteen signalized intersections.
The site access and circulation analyses were based on professional judgment in accordance with the
standards and methods employed by the traffic engineering community.
The trip generation rates for the proposed school were based on surveys that Hexagon Transportation
Consultants, Inc. conducted at five Rocketship schools in San Jose between 2012 and 2014. The
magnitude of traffic added to the roadway system by the project was estimated by multiplying the trip
generation rates by the size of the project (600 Students). The traffic generated by the school would
comprise trips by staff, visitors, non-working parents, and working parents. There will be approximately
32 staff members at the site. Hexagon estimates that 60% of parents will drop off students on the way
to work, while the remaining 40% of parents will drop off students and return home.
Based on the surveyed trip generation rates, the project would generate 578 trips during the AM peak
hour and 314 trips during PM peak hour. The project would produce 314 inbound and 264 outbound
trips during the AM peak hour, and 128 inbound and 186 outbound trips during the PM peak hour

The location and limited access to the project site would cause some project trips to use nearby

very small. Similarly, the traffic increase on Brodie Drive is expected to be very small under either
access scenario. Brodie Drive might be used as an alternative to Sylvandale Avenue by some traffic,
but it is not expected that they would achieve any time savings on the route. The City has not
established any policies or thresholds regarding neighborhood streets.
The City of San Jose’s Traffic Calming Policy for Residential Neighborhoods states that developments
should eliminate or minimize adverse impacts on neighborhood streets. As such, the City may place
conditions of approval on proposed new developments to reduce or eliminate neighborhood intrusion.

1. Construction of a new traffic signal. The signal would control the outbound project
driveway and the Andrew Hill High School parking lot driveway, which are offset by
approximately 110 feet. The signal would provide for left turns out of the project, and both left
turns in and out of Andrew Hill High School. A crosswalk could be provided between the two
offset driveways. Due to its proximity to the existing traffic signal at Senter Road and Capitol
Expressway, signal coordination is recommended. The signal would reduce the left-turn storage

2. Allow U-turns on Senter Road. Currently, the roadway width is not sufficient to allow for U-
turns on southbound Senter Road. Thus, roadway widening would be necessary in order to
accommodate U-turns. One location where U-turns may be provided is at the Andrew Hill High
School main parking lot driveway. Senter Road would need to be widened by approximately 6
feet on the east side of the street starting at the high school driveway. The street would
transition back to the existing width approximately 80 feet north of the driveway. During peak
periods immediately before and after the high school begins and ends, traffic using this left-turn
pocket is quite heavy and extends past the outbound Rocketship driveway. In order for
outbound Rocketship traffic to be able to safely access this left-turn pocket to complete a U-turn,
it is recommended that school start and end times be offset by at least 30 minutes.
Another location where U-turns may be provided is at Carpentier Way. Widening would occur
along the east side of the street gradually transitioning from the existing width to add up to 7 feet
in width and then transitioning back to the existing width over a distance of approximately 120
feet. To prevent vehicles from attempting to complete U-turns at other locations where there is
insufficient width, the median would be extended from where it currently ends just south of the
midblock crosswalk to Carpentier Way. The extended median would eliminate left turn access to
driveways along this segment of Senter Road.
At both locations, the improvements would require relocation of the existing sidewalk and
acquisition of additional right of way equal to the roadway widening. As under the full-access
alternative, allowing for U-turns on Senter Road would result in a significant impact at the
intersection of Senter Road and Capitol Expressway during the AM peak hour. The impact could
be mitigated by offsetting the start time of the proposed Rocketship school and the high school
by at least 30 minutes. The provision of outbound left turns from the project would eliminate the
intrusion of project trips within nearby neighborhoods.

The site access was evaluated to determine the adequacy of the site’s driveway with regard to the
following: traffic volume, delays, vehicle queues, geometric design, corner sight distance, and truck
access. Under the limited-access alternative, the project site would contain two one-way driveways that
connect to form an elongated loop around the perimeter of the surface parking lot provided in front of
the school buildings. Unlike other Rocketship school sites in the area that gate off portions of the
circulation aisle during school hours and open it only during drop-off and pick-up periods, the entire
perimeter drive isle at this site would be open to traffic at all times and separated from the remainder of
the school property by a fence.
The northern driveway would serve inbound traffic and the southern driveway would serve outbound
traffic. Because of the raised median on Senter Road along the project frontage, access into and out of
the project will be limited to right turns only. With this turn restriction, delay for vehicles entering and
exiting the site will be minimized.

the proposed new Rocketship School be offset from those at Andrew P. Hill High School by at least 15
The site plan does not indicate where student loading and unloading would occur. Hexagon
recommends that the drop-off/pick-up zone be designated along the curb on the southern edge of the
site. The student loading zone should be approximately 125 feet in length and begin just east of the
curve and extend towards the exit driveway. The loading zone would allow five vehicles in each lane to
load/unload simultaneously. School staff or volunteers should direct traffic and place cones in the drive
aisles while students load/unload. After all students have cleared the loading zone, staff should remove
the cones and allow traffic to move again so that the next 10 vehicles can enter the loading zone. Staff
members or parent volunteers should be stationed along the length of the student loading zone to
assist students in and out of vehicles and ensure they safely walk to the school.
School drop-off and pick-up operations and resulting queues were observed at Rocketship Mateo
Sheedy Elementary on 11/27/12 and Rocketship Si Se Puede Academy on 12/4/12. Based on our
observations, it is estimated that 525 feet of queuing space would be needed for drop-off operations
and 450 feet of queue storage would be needed for pick-up operations. Longer queues were observed
during the morning drop off than the afternoon pick-up because all grades start at the same time
whereas dismissal times vary by grade level and some students remain on site to participate in after
school programs. Including the storage space within and upstream of the loading zone and excluding
the vehicle stacking space downstream of the loading zone, the site plan shows that on-site queue

The project proposes a single entrance driveway and a single exit driveway on Senter Road. This is
denoted as the limited access alternative because currently there is a raised median adjacent to the
project site, thus access to and from the project site would be limited to right turns only. The City of San
Jose has requested analysis of a full access alternative. Under this scenario, the project would have
access through the adjacent property immediately to the south currently occupied by the Seven Trees
Baptist Church. A single full-access driveway located opposite the Andrew Hill High School driveway
would be shared by the proposed Rocketship School and the adjacent church use. The new four-way
intersection would operate under signal control.
Traffic conditions at the study intersections were analyzed for the weekday AM and PM peak hours of
traffic. The proposed Rocketship school will start classes at 7:55 AM for all grades. Students in grade K
will be dismissed at 3:45 PM, students in grades 1 and 2 will be dismissed at 4:00 PM, and students in
grades 3 through 5 will be dismissed at 4:10 PM. Before and after school programming would start at
7:15 AM and end at 6:00 PM. On early dismissal days (Wednesday), students in grade K will be
dismissed at 1:50 PM, students in grades 1 and 2 will be dismissed at 2:00 PM, and students in grades
3 through 5 will be dismissed at 2:10 PM. The peak hour of school traffic in the morning would coincide
with the AM peak hour of commute traffic (generally between 7:00 and 9:00 AM). The peak hour of
school traffic in the afternoon would occur before the PM peak hour of commute traffic (typically
between 4:00 and 6:00 PM). However, trips associated with after school programming would be added
to the PM peak commute hour. It is during these peak commute periods that traffic is busiest and the
impact on the roadway system by traffic from the school would be greatest.

i.b: Level of Service Standards and Methodology

page.text: Traffic conditions at the study intersections were evaluated using level of service (LOS). Level of
Service is a qualitative description of operating conditions ranging from LOS A, or free-flow conditions
with little or no delay, to LOS F, or jammed conditions with excessive delays. The various analysis
The City of San Jose level of service standards were used to evaluate the signalized study
intersections. The City of San Jose evaluates intersection levels of service based on the Highway
Capacity Manual (HCM) 2000 method using the TRAFFIX software. This methodology evaluates
on the basis of average control delay time for all vehicles at the
intersection. Since TRAFFIX also is the CMP designated intersection level of service methodology, the
City of San Jose methodology employs the CMP default values for the analysis parameters.
San Jose level of service standard for signalized intersections is LOS D or better. The correlation
between delay and level of service is shown in Table 2.
The designated level of service methodology for the CMP also is the 2000 HCM operations method for
signalized intersections, using TRAFFIX. The only difference in level of service standards is that in the
City of San Jose the standard is LOS D or better, and the CMP level of service standard for signalized
intersections is LOS E or better.

For selected high-demand movements at key intersections, the estimated maximum vehicle queues
were compared to the existing or planned storage capacity. The queuing analysis is presented for
informational purposes only, since neither the City of San Jose nor the CMP have defined any policies
related to queuing. Vehicle queues were calculated using a Poisson probability distribution, which
estimates the probability of “n” vehicles for a vehicle movement using the following formula:
probability of “n” vehicles in queue per lane
number of vehicles in the queue per lane
Average number of vehicles in the queue per lane (vehicles per hour per lane/signal cycles
The basis of the analysis is as follows: (1) the Poisson probability distribution is used to estimate the
percentile maximum number of queued vehicles per signal cycle for a particular movement; (2) the
estimated maximum number of vehicles in the queue is translated into a queue length, assuming 25
feet per vehicle; and (3) the estimated maximum queue length is compared to the existing or planned
available storage capacity for the movement.
The analyses of site access and on-site circulation are based on professional judgment in accordance

The remainder of this report is divided into five chapters. Chapter 2 describes existing conditions on the
existing roadway network. Chapter 3 presents the intersection operations under background conditions.
Chapter 4 presents the method used to estimate “existing plus project” traffic and its impact on the
roadway network. Also in Chapter 4 are estimates of background plus project traffic, a discussion of
potentially significant project impacts under background plus project conditions, and an analysis of the
site access and on-site circulation. Chapter 5 presents future growth conditions at the CMP
intersections. Chapter 6 presents the conclusions of the transportation impact analysis.

Regional access to the project site is provided by US 101.

page.text: The project is said to create a significant adverse impact on traffic conditions at a signalized
intersection in the City of San Jose if for either peak hour:
1. The level of service at the intersection degrades from an acceptable LOS D or better under
background conditions to an unacceptable LOS E or F under project conditions, or
2. The level of service at the intersection is an unacceptable LOS E or F under background
conditions and the addition of project trips causes both the critical-movement delay at the

An exception to this rule applies when the addition of project traffic reduces the amount of average

A significant impact by City of San Jose standards is said to be satisfactorily mitigated when measures
are implemented that would restore intersection level of service to background conditions or better.

i.b: CMP Definition of Significant Intersection Impacts

page.text: The definition of a significant impact at a CMP intersection is the same as for the City of San Jose,
except that the CMP standard for acceptable level of service at a CMP intersection is LOS E or better.
Thus, a CMP intersection that operates at LOS F would fail to meet the CMP level of service standard.

In the vicinity of the project, access to the site is limited by left-turn and U-turn restrictions. The center
median on Senter Road prohibits northbound traffic from making a left-turn into the project site. Under
the existing lane configurations, U-turns are not allowed from the south approach at the Senter
Road/Capitol Expressway intersection. Because of these restrictions, northbound traffic on Senter
Road was assigned to make a U-turn at the Senter Road/Southside Drive intersection. The center
median on Senter Road also prevents left-turn movements exiting the project site. Under the existing
lane configurations, U-turns are not allowed from the north approach at the Senter Road/Singleton
Road intersection. Because of these restrictions, about 9% of exiting traffic desiring to head north was
assigned to make a legal mid-block U-turn before the Senter Road/Singleton Road intersection. The
remaining 91% was assigned to divert through neighborhood streets, either Sylvandale Avenue or Ezie
For the full access alternative, the four-way intersection would allow left turn movements into and out of
the Rocketship School parking lot. Due to this full access, no U-turns were assigned to project trips and
fewer trips were assigned onto the neighborhood streets. Trips for the full access alternative were
largely assigned to the main arterial and collector routes.
For inbound traffic from eastbound Capitol Expressway, there is a shopping center approximately 500
feet before Senter Road that has a connection through its parking lot. Traffic might cut through this
parking lot to avoid the intersection of Senter Road/Capitol Expressway. Hexagon recommends that the
school inform its parents and staff that this shopping center is private property and should not be used
as a cut through route to the Rocketship School.
